The interactions between AIE-CDs and seven organic solvents, namely DMSO, isopropanol, DMF, acetonitrile, acetone, 1,4-dioxane, and THF, were investigated to elucidate their tunable fluorescence properties (Table 1
                        ). It is found that solvent polarity significantly influences both the emission intensity and peak wavelength of the AIE-CDs solution (Fig. 2
                        a). The tunable photoluminescent (PL) emissions are a consequence of prior interactions or surface trap states [2]. The fluorescent intensity is affected by the hydrogen bond within the surface groups of AIE-CDs and the solvent molecules [44]. Moreover, the absorbed energy of excited electrons can be released non-radiatively by altering dipole direction of various solvent molecules. Consequently, excited electrons would lose more energy in the case of a high polarity solvent compared to a less polar one. As a result, emission intensity quenching can be observed with increasing polarity, particularly in polar protic solvents such as acetic acid.
